<ArticleLayout title="PSCAD versus PSS®E: selecting the right study tool" category="Power systems" readTime="6 min read" description="A practical comparison of PSCAD and PSS/E for renewable energy grid connection studies.">
<p class="lead">PSS®E and PSCAD are complementary tools. The right choice depends on the physical phenomenon, time scale, model fidelity and decision the study needs to support.</p>
<h2>Where PSS®E is strongest</h2><p>RMS simulation is efficient for broad network assessment, longer-duration dynamic behaviour and large sets of credible contingencies. It remains central to many connection and planning studies.</p>
<h2>Where PSCAD is strongest</h2><p>EMT simulation captures fast control interactions, switching behaviour and detailed converter dynamics. It is especially important in weak-grid conditions and where inverter-based resources dominate.</p>
<h2>Avoid tool-led analysis</h2><p>The study question should determine the tool—not the other way around. Define the risk, required fidelity and acceptance criteria before building the study scope.</p>
<h2>Use results together</h2><p>Differences between RMS and EMT results can provide useful insight. A coordinated approach helps teams understand where simplified representations remain valid and where detailed controls drive system behaviour.</p>
</ArticleLayout>
